We now know that $S(t) = 0$ for all $t$ and $r = 0.01$ as well
$P = 100$. Thus, our differential equation specializes to

\begin{align*}\dfrac{dA}{dt} = 0.01t \cdot A\end{align*}

with the initial condition $A(0) = 100$. This is a \emph{separable}
differential equation that can be written as

\begin{align*}\frac{1}{A} \cdot \frac{dA}{dt} = 0.01 t\end{align*}

The first step to solve this differential equation is to integrate both
sides of the equation with respect to $t$:

\begin{align*}\int \frac{1}{A} \cdot \frac{dA}{dt} \, dt = \int 0.01 t \, dt\end{align*}

Informally, in the integrand of the integral on the left-hand side the
$dt$ terms cancel out each other. We arrive at

\begin{align*}
\int \frac{1}{A} \, dA &= 0.01 \cdot \frac{t^2}{2} + C_1\\
&= 0.005 t^2 + C_1\end{align*}

The integral on the left-hand side is just $\ln|A| + C_2$ for a constant
$C_2$. Since from the context $A$ is always nonnegative, we can ignore
the absolute value brackets. In addition, we can combine the two
constants $C_1$ and $C_2$ to a new constant that we denote by $C_3$. We
arrive at

\begin{align*}\displaystyle\ln(A) = 0.005 t^2 + C_3\end{align*}

Applying the exponential function on both side of the equation results
in

\begin{align*}A = e^{0.005 t^2 + C_3} = C_4 e^{0.005 t^2}\end{align*}

We use the initial condition $A(0) = 100$ to determine the constant
$C_4$:

\begin{align*}100 = A(0) = C_4 e^{0.005 \cdot 0^2} = C_4 e^0 = C_4\end{align*}

Hence, the solution to the initial value problem is given by the
function

\begin{align*}A(t) = 100e^{0.005 \cdot t^2}\end{align*}
